The staff truly made the visit even better. Jonathan behind the bar was friendly and knowledgeable, and John, our server, was incredibly attentive and welcoming. Great food, great drinks, and genuinely great people.

Definitely looking forward to coming back. Highly recommended!

The service is great. Not super crowded during the day so it's pretty cozy. Quiet enough for a conversation. The AI generated beer is saturated with flavor to the point it's pretty much a porter. The cheese curds were good but low in quantity. The marinara that comes with it is warm. Great variety
Julio was amazing in his recommendations and service. It’s definitely one of the few breweries that has a larger food menu. The Jalapeño breadsticks paired so well with the beers. Will visit again.

Had a great experience!  The food was great (we had the nachos with pulled pork and the pepperoni pizza).  Beer was legit as well, I had a couple of the IPA's.  Really liked the atmosphere, was low key and several people had their dogs chilling with them on the patio.
The surrounding area is also really cool, with nearby shopping, bakeries and ice cream.

Will definitely be saving for a repeat next time in town.

Excellent beer and food!  They smoke their own homemade sausage!  The beer was really awesome- especially the IPA’s!  Highly recommend California Dreamin and the Mathias!!!  The food was so good and the portions were great to make this your sole meal of the day!  Went on Christmas Eve and had great service and a really knowledgeable bartender/server to help with beer choices!  Another on the repeat list!

formatted_address: 3411 N Halsted St, Chicago, IL 60657, USA
name: The Chicago Diner - Lakeview

reviews.text: This was a cute vegan diner that had a plethora of options. The chili, mini cornbread, tostadas, and cinnamon roll were excellent. The cinnamon roll was so good that I forgot to take a picture. The only downside is that the restaurant is very small, so the staff seem to rush guests out after they've finished eating. Understandable and it's appreciated in the grander scheme. Hopefully, in the future, they will expand or move to a larger building. I hope to visit again in the future!

Food is so good. Service was excellent. Had a Cuban Sandwich. My friends had a meatless meatloaf. For dessert we had the carrot cake. Very enjoyable dinner. I go to a lot of vegetarian/vegan restaurants because a family member is vegetarian and I highly recommend this restaurant.

It is very easy to see how the Chicago Diner has been a staple for decades now!! The ambiance is unbeatable- a skinny little building packed with retro diner kitsch, decor, and classic furnishings all with an LGBTQ+ friendly twist.

The staff was soooo warm and welcoming!! Every single team member we interacted with was just beaming with warm energy and good vibes, while also being professional and very helpful in narrowing down decisions (which I definitely needed with so many appealing options).

As a long time vegetarian happy to lean vegan, I was totally blown away by the quality of the food as well! There were several dishes I would never has guessed were vegan, they were just so packed with flavor, perfectly seasoned, and even “creamy” or “cheesy” without ever imparting that overly processed vegan-trying-too-hard flavor.

We got the crispy potato skin bites stuffed with Mac & cheese (!!!), minced jalapeños, tomato, crunchy “bacon”, green onions and a sooo yummy “sour cream” sauce! I would recommend these to anyone…. Every bite was incredible and the only problem with them is actually sharing them once every tries them 😅

The absolute hands down star of the show though was the Truffle Mushroom & Lentil Meatloaf! I feel like I have been searching for this meal my entire life. I’ve had a few other veggie and even lentil based “patties” claiming to be meatloaf, but were really just mushy sculptures that broke down into a soup under bland gravy. This dish was the opposite of that. A masterpiece!! Every ingredient in the patty was the perfect texture, you could see fresh veggies and lentils shredded and cooked and bound together flawlessly. The gravy was the best I’ve ever had. I told the server I am not a huge truffle fan when it is overdone and she assured me it was subtle and used well, and wow she was right! The truffle notes were there, but just enough there to enhance an umami like sensation with the mushroom and give the gravy a delicious savory aspect. The gravy was so thick and held together perfectly, and the meatloaf was cooked so incredible that there was some crunch and crisp to the edges that held up even after sitting under the gravy for the time it took me to finish the dish. The potatoes and green beans on the side were perfectly cooked and seasoned as well.

Overall I would rate the Chicago Diner 10 out of 5 stars if I could!! I will be raving about it and recommending it to friends forever. I can’t wait to come back and try the entire menu… I’ve heard the milkshakes are not to be missed!

I just want to thank this business and all its staff for creating such magic for us to enjoy.  🫶🌈🏳️‍⚧️
Absolutely fantastic! In town for business, traveling with a Vegan, and decided to make a detour…well worth it. The Reuben and Mushroom Melt were awesome. Nice classic diner vibe, chill staff.

I'm glad I experienced this... but there's much better vegan breakfast food in the area.

Not sure how you mess up biscuits and gravy, but mine was bland and the biscuits were flat and kinda bad.
Bacon for sure could've been crisped up and wasn't.
Shake was good, wings were good.

Took about 45 minutes to get our coffee...

If this was cheap, sure, it'd be fine and worth a quick bite.

This was one of our most expensive and disappointing meals in the vegan chicago scene.

formatted_address: 875 N Michigan Ave, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: The Cheesecake Factory

reviews.text: We always come here for lunch when visiting Chicago. I have been here at least a couple of dozen times (we normally split the chicken Romano dinner portion - love it), but today was the best one. Everything was perfect, and Keith was the most outstanding server we have ever had and could easily be a manager here too. It was great! Thanks

Lovely decor and wonderful service made this place ideal for a mid-morning sweet treat. While they do have a full food menu they were happy for us just to order a couple of slices of cheesecake and as well as them being massive they were delicious!

It was strange for there not to be any prices on the menu but fortunately it ended up being reasonable value when the bill arrived, and there’s certainly something for all tastes available. There’s also a full bar and large selection of cocktails available too. I’d recommend!

Today, we had a wonderful experience at The Cheesecake Factory. The service was excellent, and the staff were very attentive to our needs. The restaurant’s atmosphere was unique and original, which made the dining experience even more enjoyable. Additionally, the bathrooms were spotless, which shows their commitment to cleanliness and customer care.

Overall, it was a great visit, and I highly recommend it to anyone looking for a pleasant dining experience! 🇺🇸

A wide variety of great food on an extensive menu. The ahi tuna is always good and the miso salmon was perfect. Loved the tiramisu cheesecake tonight. The only way you get a bad cheesecake is if you order a flavor you don't like. Don't do that.

A Decent Dinner After a Sky-High View at The Cheesecake Factory (Chicago)

My wife and I decided to grab dinner at The Cheesecake Factory after taking in the breathtaking views of Chicago from the 94th floor. The location was certainly convenient, and despite it being a weeknight, we were pleasantly surprised by the relatively short 10-minute wait for a table.
The atmosphere inside was just as expected – a bustling and lively environment with a good energy. It felt like a comfortable and inviting space for a casual dinner.

When it came to the food, there were definitely some highlights. The Brussel sprouts were a fantastic start. They were perfectly cooked and bursting with flavor, and the complimentary bread and butter served alongside were a nice touch. My Sesame Ginger Chicken was also a winner. The chicken was tender, and the sesame ginger glaze was absolutely delicious – a great balance of sweet and savory. My wife thoroughly enjoyed her Rene's Chicken Sandwich, particularly praising the fresh and flavorful salad that accompanied it.
However, not everything was a home run. While the soup was acceptable, it wasn't particularly memorable. The main issue we encountered was with the Rene's Chicken Sandwich itself. While the salad was a hit, the sandwich had a noticeable smell that my wife found off-putting. She still ate it, but it definitely detracted from the overall enjoyment of that dish.

The service, on the other hand, was truly awesome. Our server was attentive, friendly, and efficient, making sure we had everything we needed throughout our meal. Our non-alcoholic cocktails were also well-made and refreshing.

Overall, our experience at The Cheesecake Factory in Chicago was a mixed bag but leaned towards the positive. The convenient location after our visit to the observation deck was a plus, and the short wait time was appreciated. We thoroughly enjoyed some of the dishes, particularly the Brussel sprouts and the Sesame Ginger Chicken, and the service was exceptional. However, the unpleasant smell from the chicken sandwich was a notable downside.

Here's a quick summary:
Pros:
* Convenient location after visiting the Chicago observation deck.
* Short 10-minute wait time.
* Good overall environment.
* Delicious Brussel sprouts with complimentary bread and butter.
* Excellent Sesame Ginger Chicken.
* Flavorful salad accompanying the Rene's Chicken Sandwich.
* Awesome and attentive service.
* Well-made non-alcoholic cocktails.

Cons:
* Soup was just okay.
* The Rene's Chicken Sandwich had an unpleasant smell.

Would we go back? Possibly. We enjoyed enough of the experience, and the service was truly outstanding. However, we would likely steer clear of the Rene's Chicken Sandwich next time. It's a decent option for a casual dinner, especially if you're looking for variety and are in the area.

formatted_address: 60 W Ontario St, Chicago, IL 60654, USA
name: Chicago Chop House

reviews.text:
This place was on a small list of great steakhouses to try while in Chicago. I am so glad we made it in. The food did not disappoint!

We started off with a unique cocktail which was recommended by our server Julio. Fun fact, Julio won a cocktail contest with this drink and we can see why! It was unique and refreshing, great way to start the evening. We shared a tomahawk steak because it was a special occasion and decided to splurge. On the sides we had wild mushrooms which were amazing and complimented the steak and also ordered the potato pancakes. Truthfully I was not impressed by potato pancakes they were very bland and oily. Waiter asked if we weren’t happy with them and I told him the truth then they were replaced with grilled asparagus which tasted as good as the steak! Overall great experience love the atmosphere, staff was friendly and made great recommendations, pricing is in line with fine dining, would definitely come back if in the area. Well done Chop House!

The Chophouse in Chicago delivers a stellar dining experience with a refined atmosphere and exceptional service. From start to finish, it was clear that this is a place where quality is a priority. We began with the Delmonico steak, which was absolutely amazing—perfectly cooked, tender, and bursting with flavor. It easily stole the spotlight as the standout dish of the evening. The dry-aged filet was a close second, offering a melt-in-your-mouth texture and a rich, deep flavor that did not disappoint.

The Lobster Mac and Cheese, while flavorful, fell a bit short in terms of value. For the price, we expected more lobster in the dish, and the amount served didn’t quite match the hefty price tag. That said, the creamy sauce and perfectly cooked pasta still made it a tasty side.

Overall, The Chophouse is a fantastic spot for steak lovers, and while the Lobster Mac and Cheese didn’t fully hit the mark, the Delmonico and filet more than made up for it. I’d give it a solid 4 out of 5 stars and highly recommend it for anyone looking for a memorable steakhouse experience in Chicago.

If you can only go to one restaurant in Chicago make it this one.  The food is top quality! But that is not all. The atmosphere is so relaxing and serene. The employees make you feel like family.  Derick at the bar and Niko our server were amazing. Helped us choose the drink and cut of steak best for us.  When ever we come to Chicago this is the place we make sure we  visit.

One of, if not the best steakhouse in Chicago. Service was excellent. We got the bay window on second floor.
The delmonico steak delicious and aged to perfection.
Our Server Grace was knowledgeable of steak menu, and history of restaurant.

Great restaurant. First time here. Had reservations, table was ready when we arrived. Nice atmosphere. Service was great. Our server was attentive. Good menu options. My favorite was the Lobster Escargot - soooooo delicious! The waygu meatballs were good too. Wine was excellent. We ordered a few different family sharing sides. Fries, asparagus, brussel sprouts and the mash potatoes. All were excellent. I ordered the rack of lamb and it was cooked perfectly, melt in your mouth good.
They say have your phones on vibrate or silent when in the restaurant.
Overall all a great experience. I definitely enjoyed everything.

formatted_address: 1120 N State St, Chicago, IL 60610, USA
name: Lou Malnati's Pizzeria

reviews.text:
If you want to experience hey Chicago’s deep dish pizza, then this is the place to come.  They have other branches as well!
For a fair heads up: toppings are not a lot and it’s more of an experience as I had only one piece of mushroom on a one whole slice! The rest is sauce and cheese!

As a New Yorker and a lover of pizza and having tried all kinds around the world, while in Chicago I enjoyed having some of their classic deep dish. Lou Malnati’s is one of several with a good reputation for their pies. We went for the classic sausage pie, that is less thick than others in Chicago but unique in its own way, a very fresh and natural tasting tomato sauce, lots of creamy mozzarella, okay sausage and nice and crispy crust. I have had other deep dish pies in Chicago that were probably a little bit better but this was not bad at all. Service was good, place was busy and a bit loud.
My wife, our friends, and I came here for lunch. We ordered the deep dish pepperoni and the buffalo chicken pizza on thin crust. They were good. Our waiter was friendly and helpful!
Worth a stop while in Chicago. Great food and service. We came specifically for the deep dish as it was our first time in Chicago. Pizza is filling so don’t over order. Enjoy!

I could not go to Chicago without trying deep dish, pizza! I am gluten-free, and they had an excellent option. I will say that, for the most part, I ate the toppings and the sauce, but they were really good. I enjoyed the sauce a lot!

formatted_address: 1028 N Rush St, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: Gibsons Bar & Steakhouse

reviews.text:
Famous restaurant in Chicago that specializes in steaks. The food is good but I will not say outstanding for the price paid,  Started with oysters as an appetizer they were fresh but very small hard to taste any flavor. The Caesar salad was fine nothing to brag about..
The two best items were the Brussel sprouts were amazing! and the fillet was perfectly cooked. The béarnaise  was very average. Glad I ordered the peppercorn sauce, which was very good.. If you like an energetic active restaurant this you will like Gibsons.

I LOVE taking people here for their first time.  Such was the case on this visit.  This restaurant is WILDLY popular so make a reservation but be warned.  They run behind on reservations frequently - as much as 45 minutes - so be prepared for that.

On this occasion, our reservation was running behind so we had a great time chatting at the packed bar.  Our reservation was called and we were seated about 30 minutes later than our reservation.  Much to our delight one of the floor managers brought us a delicious shrimp cocktail with humongous shrimp on the house with apologies for the reservation being behind schedule.  Nice touch.

The place was hopping and our service was very good, given the amount of business - and this was a Tuesday night!   We had the House cut ribeye and split one of the Australian huge lobster tails.   My friend loved it !!   He said it was the best lobster he ever had and the second best steak he ever had.  A four-top next to us even offered to share their desserts with us which were scrumptious.

Please note - this particular Gibsons is lots of fun - but it is vibrant and frenetic.  Pretty loud atmosphere.  If you want to try Gibsons but prefer a more quiet and romantic setting pick one of the other locations - although they can get pretty energetic also.

We love this place !

One of my husband’s and my favorite go-to spots for quick bites and drinks. It’s always bustling, which adds to the fun, lively atmosphere. We couldn’t resist ordering their famous Turtle Pie as a celebratory treat—and it did not disappoint. It’s absolutely worth every penny. Heads literally turn when it comes out, and the taste is just as impressive as the presentation!

I was very disappointed with our steak, that was the main purpose of our visit. It was overcooked on the outside and undercooked on the inside. I would never send it back because my son would be embarrassed. The bearnaise sauce was excellent. My son loved his sliders and the shrimp cocktail was amazing. I did not care for the double baked potato it looked like a baked potato with cheese melted on it vs. a traditional twice baked potato which is what I was expecting. I also didn’t want to send that back. The soup and salad were very nice but we were too full to finish either one. I wish we had room for dessert because they looked spectacular. We would definitely try it again, perhaps for lunch.

We had an absolutely fantastic experience at Gibsons. Food, service and atmosphere were all absolutely excellent. Daniel was our server for the evening and I could not fault a single thing - he was so experienced, knowledgeable, friendly and personable. Can’t wait to come back again. With love from Ireland.

formatted_address: 837 W Fulton Market, Chicago, IL 60607, USA
name: The Publican

reviews.text:
Food was 5/5 ! Clean + delicious salads for lunch. Ingredients taste fresh and high quality. The oysters were absolutely delish. Lovely simple mignonette served with it just the way I like it.
Only let down was the slow service. But the waiters were all pleasant and nice.

I went there with 3 friends. The food was ok. The service was phenomenal! The side dish we thought was absolutely delicious was the potatoes. The dressing was delicious. The salad was basically just lettuce. The eggs were bland and had HUGE chunks of what tasted like canned tomatoes. Everything else was just ok. It was pricey for just being ok. Based on the food alone, I wouldn't go back. Based on the service, I would definitely give it another chance.

An Ode to The Publican

In Fulton’s heart where markets hum,
There lives a spot where foodies come.
The Publican—both bold and bright,
A place that always gets it right…
(Well—almost always, to be fair,
But kindness floats through every chair.)

The booths, oh bliss! They close you in—
A cozy nook amidst the din.
Or gather ‘round long tables wide,
Where strangers sit and smiles abide.
A haven for your whole loud crew,
With seats for twelve and maybe two.

The menu? Witty, warm, and kind—
With plates for every taste and mind.
Pork and pickles, bread and beer,
A rustic feast awaits you here.
We hit a snag—some dishes strayed—
But Kim appeared, calm and unfrayed.

With gracious care and knowing nod,
She fixed our night (we gave a laud!).
Her kindness, like the wine, did pour,
And we’ll return forevermore.

For long before the scene got hot,
The Publican had claimed its spot.
A pioneer with charm and clout—
Still standing strong, still dishing out.

So here’s to seats and meals well-spun,
And Kim—our hero, bar to none.
To Fulton’s soul, its heart, its spark—
The Publican, a glowing mark.

The Publican offers a creative menu centered around seafood and pork, with an emphasis on global brews and communal dining. While the concept is intriguing, my experience here left much to be desired.

I visited with a party of eight, and the general sentiment was disappointment, primarily due to the pricing and portion sizes. The Hamachi, for instance, was priced at $20 for just three small slices—a detail not made clear on the menu. The server’s lack of helpfulness in explaining portions only compounded the issue. While we ordered most of the menu’s offerings, the limited selection didn’t provide much excitement.

The only standout dish was the beef-fat fries, which were well-executed and memorable. However, this alone wasn’t enough to salvage the experience.

Service was another weak point. While the mistakes were minor, the lack of attentiveness was glaring, especially when the bill exceeded $750. For a restaurant with such a high price point, the service should match the cost.

Overall, I wouldn’t recommend The Publican. While the concept is appealing, the execution in terms of value, service, and menu variety falls short of expectations.

Went for brunch and was a bit underwhelmed by the menu. With that said I landed on the shakshuka and as soon as I came out I could tell by the smell and colour I was not going to enjoy it. There was a serious lack of seasoning and the tomatoes were undercooked. It ended up. tasting like an underdevloped plate of canned tomatoes with a bunch of raw onions and some fetta thrown on top. They have a bunch of James Beard awards at the front door from the early 2010s and it seemed a bit odd to have 6 years running that ended abruptly. The full menu must be better.

formatted_address: 110 W Illinois St, Chicago, IL 60654, USA
name: Sunda New Asian - River North

reviews.text: An amazing experience all-around!! The reservation process was straightforward and the service 👨‍🍳 was absolutely phenomenal!! It was actually my birthday 🎂 when I visited, and I had marked that on my reservation when booking. When I arrived at the restaurant, to my surprise, there was a birthday 🎈 card on our table and also a nice coconut 🥥 cake dessert at the end (for free)!! The food itself, though not cheap, was very high-quality, unique, and super filling. The portions were extremely generous 🎁. I was so full that I even had extras 🥡 to take home, which usually doesn't happen for me. Our waiter was also super nice and kept checking in with us to make sure it was an enjoyable ✅ experience. This is a top-notch establishment and the perfect place for a downtown meal in the Windy 🍃 City!!

Sunda was a standout this weekend while my husband and I visited Chicago for the first time. We were lucky to walk in and get a two top, despite the restaurant being very busy for a Friday evening. They seated us quickly and even offered us sake shots!

Our server, Caden, was so welcoming and gave us great recommendations on food and drinks. He also offered us a complimentary birthday dessert on our way out. The atmosphere was lively, on the louder side, but nothing I wouldn’t expect from a place that has a nice crowd in and out. We had a great time and hope to be back one day!

Absolutely great sushi and Asian cuisine. This place has a great vibe and service. We organized a private corporate event for 40 people and it don’t disappoint. We got a host of sushi rolls, warm appetizers, vegetarian, meats and vegan options. Every thing was well put together and delicious.

My friend recommended this place during a work trip to Chicago when I was craving something Asian fusion. We tried Bulgogi taco, oxtail dumplings, and crispy rice (which you can order half/half & I strongly recommend you do!!). For 2 ladies, that was plenty of food.
My favorite was crispy rice with wagyu, and my friend loved the bulgogi taco. Heard they have great cocktails and great happy hr, but we didn't get a chance to try this time. Maybe next time :)

The ambiance and service is very good. We bought the Tuna Pizza and Avocado crispy rice. We went in for brunch on a Saturday, the crowd is generally more. Avocado Crispy Rice was prepared well. The Tuna Pizza had the tuna completely raw and we didn’t like that very much. The quantity of the dishes were also very less for the price of the dish.

formatted_address: 2105 S State St, Chicago, IL 60616, USA
name: Reggies Chicago

reviews.text:
The coolest venue I've ever been to! Table service during a punk show?! I cannot wait to come back.

The food was good and reasonable, the people were awesome and the bands were excellent.

See you soon reggies.
It’s such a cool like cozy place! I get real gothic vibes! I love dark spaces it gives me peace. The vibes and the decor were cool. Not too crowded or unruly. Good bites and drinks I recommend.

I've been going here for over 13 YEARS to get their wings, and today I've had the worst experience. I order jumbo wings, (I'm addicted) only to receive super small wings. I called and spoke with one rude lady who wouldn't take any of my concerns seriously. I asked to speak with a manager to no avail. I offered to provide photos of my order but she was too busy defending the supplier "they've used for years" when I asked for a refund, she stated there was nothing she could do for me! Incredible, after all of these years, I will never spend another dime in this place.
Do these look jumbo to you?

Really solid pub food!  A place to go and have a good time!  Old style pub, with very attentive service.  Food comes out quickly.  Nice selection of beer, bottled and draughts!  Comedy night is great!  Neat authentic neighborhood spot, close to Mccormick Place!

I was there last night on the rooftop around "8pm for my friend birthday and our waitress "caucasian early 20s long hair never gave her name. I order the MAIN STAGE burger. I asked her what comes on it she oh, she is the points in the menu smh in which I asked the question because it did not specify Then I ordered a old-fashioned. She bought a drink to me. I tasted a self and did not like it. I let her know and she told me that there are 1 million different ways to make old-fashioned. I stated to her that that is not true and can she explain to me the different ways she proceeded to tell me that she could not smh She exchanged my drink, brought my drink to the table and slammed it down. At that point I was ready to go Then my food came out, and my burger was hard as a brick extremely dry. The burger was cold , hard & burnt in which my tooth broke in half ,tater tots were room temperature .At that point I did not want to Complain anymore  it was my friend's birthday, and I did not want to ruin the night. This was one of my favorite laid-back spots ever and for us to experience such poor customer service no knowledgeable of  the menu and just cold Hearted disrespect I do not recommend this place

formatted_address: 17 W Adams St, Chicago, IL 60603, USA
name: The Berghoff Restaurant

reviews.text: A classic old school German restaurant. The Berghoff is serving up delicious, hearty food with excellent service. My server, Esther, was fantastic. She made me feel welcomed from the get-go. The Bavarian pretzel with the cheese sauce was delicious. The bratwurst with sauerkraut on a toasted pretzel roll was really tasty. The side salad was very good as well. The massive amounts of wood paneling and wall size murals really add to the experience. Highly recommend the Berghoff for food and service!

On the last night of a very long business trip, my colleagues and I stopped at Berghoff Restaurant - we read that it was an iconic place so we wanted to check it out! This is a MUST try place!

Chris, our server, was amazing! He was very attentive, had a great sense of humor and made fantastic recommendations.

The food was super authentic - I love perogies and the fresh root beer was delicious! The dessert was amazing too! Portions are on the larger side (especially the mashed potatoes!) but it felt like a good value.

The food was very good. And this place has the best beer I have ever tried in the US. The atmosphere was very calm, there wasn’t a lot of people. The place itself is very pretty and service was amazing. Servers would come up to us to give some water EVERY TIME we would run out - we wouldn’t even ask them. They are very attentive to their customers. The wait for food wasn’t long at all, and food selection was wide.

Nice pub-like atmosphere, quick service.  The food was good, but not the best schnitzel I've had.  I did really like the giant pretzel, though.  And the schnitzel wasn't bad by any means, just not top tier in my experience.  Still, if I spent more time in Chicago I'd be tempted to go back and try one of the sausage dishes.  And indulge in another pretzel.

The food was amazing, their Rueben was to die for and I’ll never be able to have another one and think of it as good. Their root beer is perfectly smooth with that add on hint of vanilla. The service was friendly and kind (thank you Isiah) the price is definitely worth it. If you are ever in Chicago you have to go to Berghoff, the experience calls for it

formatted_address: 565 W Jackson Blvd, Chicago, IL 60661, USA
name: Lou Mitchell's

reviews.text:
This place was fantastic. Everything was well made, delicious and huge. No, really, huge.

Do not skip their baked goods or homemade jelly. 🤤

It took a bit to get our food. The wait was worth it, but I’d say it’s not a quick stop place.

I was surprised about their coffee. I’m a hard more-milk-and-sugar-than-coffee, but somehow loved their black coffee as it was.

It was packed. Even though they have tons of space,there were tons of people waiting to be seated at all times.

Everyone who works here looks like they’ve worked here for forever. They all are nice enough, but in a distracted (they’re super busy) and very city like way. I loved it.

It has this charm to it… I don’t know how to explain it. Can’t wait to come back!

This rating is based on the food. The service was fine. I got egg Benedict which came with sliced potatoes that were unevenly cooked. Some were hard, some soft, some rubbery and some raw. My wife good the French toast special which was basically not editable. It was hard as a rock in spots and the softer spots were flavorless. The only good thing was the free donut hole they give you at the beginning. We spent $50 plus a tip for the 2 plates and 2 diet sodas and we were very disappointed. 100% would not recommend

My husband and I were visiting from Seattle. We waited in line for about 30 minutes but it was definitely worth the wait. We enjoyed the pecan roll, a Denver omelet, a BLT, and a pancake. We loved it all and would recommend the stop if visiting. We loved our server Mickey! She took care of us and made  it a great breakfast.

A Chicago staple! Lou Mitchell’s has been around for over a century! That is testament to success! This place is popular so expect to wait. The staff is friendly and accommodating. The restaurant is cozy but they move quick on the delivery of food. I had an omelette (spinach, mushroom, bacon), it was served with potatoes and your choice of bread. It was tasty and plentiful. Also, they provide complimentary doughnut holes. It is a busy and high energy environment! A great place to stop before or after that trip to Union Station, which is literally 1/2 block away! Stop by…give them a try!

A classic Chicago staple. One of the best breakfast in the city, the fluffy eggs were just top notch everything here was perfect and the coffee is just awesome. They kept bringing in coffee again and again. Would definitely visit again. The breakfast so filling that I didn’t eat anything for the rest of the day.

formatted_address: 958 W Wrightwood Ave, Chicago, IL 60614, USA
name: Lou Malnati's Pizzeria

reviews.text: Great deep dish and thin crust. We tried the personal sizes of both to get a feel for each type. Couldn’t pick a fave! They make their deep dish with corn meal and that adds a different taste to the pizza. Very good! Sauce was amazing.

First time in Chicago and Lou Malnati’s was recommended to us by a local we met at the airport. The BEST DEEP DISH pizza ever! I was only able to eat one slice considering how thick the pizza was. We made reservations and were seated right away. We waited about 15-20 minutes before getting our order taken let alone get our water/drink order taken BUT the waitress was so apologetic that we couldn’t even be mad. We felt bad as there were only two waitress and our waitress in particular was running all over the restaurant doing her best to wait on her tables. The pizza does take 30 minutes to cook so come in about 30-40 minutes before you anticipate to eat and grab a drink! There are no beers on tap, only canned seltzers and beers. Definitely the highlight of our Chicago trip !

This was the second pizza place we visited because our first pick pizza place had a 40 minute wait time with a very long line out the door of people waiting to be seated.

This place didn't have any waiting and I guess that should have made us question this choice but, it supposedly had great reviews? At least so I was told by someone in our party.

Although the place wasn't very busy, about 4 or 5 occupied small tables, including ours, mostly seating one or 2 diners each our table being the exception seating the 5 of us. The menu stated it would be a 30 minute wait for a pizza and it took that and longer.

Our server was very attentive refilling our water glasses at least a couple of times as we waited for the one small thin crust pizza one person in our party ordered along with the large Chicago pepperoni and sausage deep dish pizza everyone else ordered. We wanted to taste the hype.

Once the pizzas arrived, our server cut and served us the slices of the large Chicago deep dish pizza. That was a very nice touch. The pizza did look good. Looks can be deceiving. The ingredients were fresh tasting and the pizza had the perfect amount of sauce and the crust had the right amount of crispy on the edges of each slice however, dough without salt is just NOT good. The pizza dough had no salt so that left it tasting super bland. Did someone forget to use salt or was this what this particular restaurant's idea of a good pizza is? We'll never know since we were tourists visiting Chicago for the first time.  If this is what deep dish pizza is supposed to be like then, no thanks. Yes, I would never eat another deep dish Chicago pizza in Chicago just for the lack of salt in the crust despite the toppings being very good. Salt is extremely important in dough. Bread without salt is tasteless and this was what the experience of eating this pizza was like. The better pizza was the thin crust pizza. It was also fresh tasting and because the crust was so thin, the toppings did a better job of masking the lack of salt.

Would I be rushing back to this place? If I'm ever in Chicago again, this place would be a pass. Nice server though.

Didn't dine. Took a pizza to go. Customized the pizza with thin crust, and anchovies, jalapeno peppers onions and mushrooms with cheese and tomato sauce. Try this out guys. We loved it. This Pizza with red wine was amazing. We ordered large pizza and they cut it. The crust was too thin for my liking but it was tasty so I ignored the thinness of the crust.

Can't say much about the service since I didn't dine in but my experience when I ordered was nothing bad except that the hostesses gives one a very nonchalant attitude. There is no commitment to come across as professional and courteous and make the customer feel good about their interaction with the hostesses. When I asked the girl, do I pay now or when I pick up, the response was very abrupt and she stated, "you can pay now". Now lot of us might think, what is wrong with that, however I beg to differ. You are at your work place and you need to use appealing language that is garnished with respect and courteousness. I'm mentioning this coz the response struck me as odd and unappealing. I did of course pay it as she asked me however I always believe, you should always try to make an interaction pleasant and nice as that is the only way, we can enjoy the same in this society. If we all act nonchalant towards one another and have a don't care attitude, we will all be recipients of negativity and unpleasantness.

Have ordered delivery and the last 4 times, the pizza has come soaking wet in grease. Not only is the crust completely soaked and mushy, but it has soaked through the box so the cardboard is also mush. This is not an exaggeration - there's a little pool of grease. And yes, we request it 'well done' and uncut.

I hate that I have to be "that person" writing a negative review but we've asked multiple times for this to be resolved and nothing has stuck. Hoping other people see this and don't get stuck in the same crummy experience. We've ordered from the location on Lincoln and didn't have this issue, and they cited that they've been getting more business bc people are coming in complaining of this same thing at the LP location. $60 for delivery and this is the quality. What!

formatted_address: 300 N La Salle Dr, Chicago, IL 60654, USA
name: Chicago Cut Steakhouse

reviews.text: Top-notch dining with a view! Chicago Cut Steakhouse delivered an unforgettable experience. Service was excellent! The seafood tower was incredibly fresh, and the ribeye was perfectly cooked and flavorful. We sat outside with vibrant views of the river—such a beautiful setting for a delicious meal. Highly recommend!

Lovely riverside steak house. Beef was phenomenal. Too bad they didn't have the bone in prime when we visited. Extensive selection of affordable wine list. Fish is not their strength. Service is attentive and quick.

By FAR the BEST steakhouse in the city! Everything was top tier and AMAZING! From the service, the view, the atmosphere, down to the food! There is nothing but good things here ! Matt took care of us through the night and was very attentive and informative. Whatever they are doing here, I hope they never change their ways and we will never go to any other establishment again! Thank you all for taking such care and pride of the establishment ! We cannot wait to be back!

This is our first trip to Chicago and we went to the Chicago Cut Steakhouse as it was recommended to us by a friend of the owner. He wasn't there but we were treated like royalty. Sitting out on the deck, it's beautiful to watch the city life go by.
Our food was truly excellent, both of us had filet mignon, centre cut - both cooked to perfection. Sides were delicious. Starters too!
Desserts were too big and neither of us could finish them.
Big shout to Tom who served us and Lorna from Galway who is here on a J1.
Highly, highly recommended.

We had never been anywhere like this before. I don't even have words..... it was simply eccentric, elegant, and fabulous. I'm so grateful that we got to experience this place. Me and my fiancé had steaks that cut like butter and cooked to perfection. The cake, the apps, the food. Incredible!!! Highly recommend and hopefully in a year we can come back and celebrate marriage and not just the proposal.

formatted_address: 159 W Erie St, Chicago, IL 60654, USA
name: Wildfire

reviews.text:
Stopped by Wildfire after work on a Thursday, and it was exactly what I needed to shift gears. Dim lights, polished wood, a soft buzz of conversation—it hits the perfect midpoint between upscale steakhouse and lively cocktail lounge.

Let’s talk drinks.
The Story Night cocktail is a knockout. Complex, smooth, and just the right balance of citrus and smoke. It’s the kind of drink that gets better with each sip—and might get you telling stories you swore you’d keep to yourself.

Bar Scene Bonus:
Not gonna lie, the energy at the bar was active. A couple of regulars, a few solo flyers, and at least one stylish woman making every guy suddenly forget they were “just grabbing one.” Charismatic, confident, and clearly enjoying the attention—she brought a whole lot of spark to the corner of the bar. After-work crowd was definitely wide-eyed.

Service & Ambience:
The bartenders? Sharp and intuitive. They don’t hover, but they’re always right there when your glass gets low. Music’s on point—classic without being corny. And the whole space hums with just enough possibility to make you linger.

Bottom line:
Whether you’re there for the steak, the Story Night, or the stories you’ll leave with—Wildfire keeps things interesting.

Great service! I forgot the waitresses name but she was very sweet and quirky the food was absolutely fantastic I took my dad there for Father's Day he loved it and gave compliments to the chef definitely with patronize them. I also work in the area

They were absolutely wonderful and accommodating. We had a double date and they stood us up🤬. We got lost and spent 30 minutes trying to park. Then we brought parking in a full garage. We were exhausted and expected to be turned away because we were so late. This amazing staff took care of us and the food was delicious and the service was impeccable. I loved the crab cakes and scallops. My hubby🥰 had the Beef Wellington and it was delightful. We had drinks....Mango Martini with Bombay Gin.... delicious. Thank you for an exceptional dinner and a beautiful date night 😍.

The atmosphere is reminiscent of the Rat Pack Era, the restaurant was very clean. Loved the bathrooms…besides it being very clean, the I liked how the stall doors went down to the floor & gave more privacy compared to most bathrooms!

The service was top notch! Every employee that we interacted with was very kind and our server was attentive to us throughout our entire time there.

The food & drinks were absolutely incredible!! My mom and I both had the Cedar Plank Salmon with a Bourbon Glaze, and it was one of the best pieces of salmon I’ve ever had! I had a side of Mac & cheese that was super tasty, and my Mom loved her side of mashed potatoes! We then split an order of the Wildfire Chopped Salad, because my Mom said I just HAD to try it! The salad was massive, so we took some home, but its’ taste definitely lived up to the hype - SO good! We both ordered 1 of their famous Martini Flights - It’s no longer on the menu but still available to order! The flight is a bit on the pricey side, but if you’ve got the money to spend & you like martinis, it’s 100% worth the splurge!

Outstanding service and food at the bar. We wanted an excellent dinner while watching playoffs on TV.  Wildfire was perfect.  Female bartender was efficient and funny.  Porterhouse steak is delicious and a great value for a hungry man.  Raw and creamy horseradish perfectly complement the prime rib.

formatted_address: 180 S Roselle Rd, Schaumburg, IL 60193, USA
name: Bonefish Grill

reviews.text: Came here on a lunch date. With my wife 😆 Let me tell you something... we had an excellent time! The place was so nice & comfortable, the food was REALLY good, & the atmosphere & service were awesome. Thank you again Kayla. Easy parking. Just my luck, there was a spot open right by the door in the corner. Now more about the food... The Bang Bang Shrimp was out of this world!! I ordered the fish & chips for my main entrée & was very satisfied. The soup was really good, too. I would really like to come here again!! 😁

Disappointing Experience.
Unfortunately, this was the worst Bonefish location I’ve visited. The food quality was extremely poor.
The pork was undercooked, which is a serious food safety concern. I specifically asked the server to ensure it was properly prepared, but it still came out unsafe to eat.( pictures attached)
The broccoli was over-fried and unappetizing.
The bread was clearly not fresh.
The overall kitchen execution was terrible.
The only saving grace of this visit was the server, who provided excellent service despite the disappointing food.
On top of everything was extremely cold in the restaurant.
Overall, this was a complete waste of time, and I won’t be returning.

Good place to get seafood. We usually get their popular bang bang shrimp, sea bass, imperial dip and blackened mango topped salmon. This time we got their daily specials which were tasty but with experience we realized anything topped with spinach on butterfish or snappers don’t taste well.

We went for brunch on a Saturday. I was with a group of 8. We ordered a bunch of appetizers, bang bang shrimp, Imperial dip, Sashimi tuna, and Calamari.  All were delicious and better than expected. The main courses were delicious. We had Blackened Salmon, Shrimp, and Mahi Mahi, Fontina pork tenderloin, and 3 course dinner of Kung pao shrimp bowl. All were wonderful and everyone was very pleased.  The service was excellent and we had a wonderful experience.

Wow... It's been awhile since I've been to Bonefish however I will definitely make it a regular place to eat at from now on.

The gin martini was delicious...

The appetizer beef and ginger dumplings was absolutely incredible!

The brussel salad was perfect to split ... And was excellent!

This was followed up with the salmon and a lemon butter sauce that was phenomenal ! Along with mashed potatoes and fresh broccoli it was perfect.

And last but not least was the service. I really have to compliment the server who took care of us.

Phil was attentive and perfect with timing. Beyond that... It felt like we were served by a maitre d rather than by a server... This place just has a classier way of doing things. It shows with the staff here.

My new go to for special occasions and special friends to go out and eat will be here at bonefish.

Oh and I can't neglect to say that the prices are still very very reasonable.

formatted_address: 225 N Michigan Ave, Chicago, IL 60601, USA
name: Sweetwater Tavern & Grille (Michigan Plaza - Chicago)

reviews.text:
The food was good. The service was amazing.

I was visiting Chicago with my mom and came across this place. We entered and it was a very good choice. They seat us immediately even when we didn't have a reservation. Our server Omar was very attentive and I really appreciated that he switched to Spanish as soon as he noticed my mom doesn't speak English. We also asked for a tortilla soup to share as a starter and he kindly divided it. Very good.

Great good, phenomenal service! I can’t remember the server’s name but he was paying his way through college, looked of mixed African-American complexion with a short Afro. He was so awesome! He also made sure to ask about any dietary restrictions or allergies. The music was great and the food came out super fast.

Highly recommend! The food was delicious and I will go back! The waiter was so nice and accommodating. We didn’t wait long for our food and the drinks were good. They add a 3% surcharge to your bill that can be waived and I thought that was a little odd. However, I’m not from Chicago and I guess that’s a thing. Also, I believe it was the AC that made a loud sound when it turned on. It was a little distracting and my friends and I were startled a few times but we got used to it. Overall, this is a wonderful restaurant and can’t wait to come back!

Came here for a get-together with friends. The place was pretty full. We had a reservation, and when we got here, we waited a bit before we were seated. It has a cool ambiance but was pretty noisy, and we had to speak loudly to hear ourselves. The staff who served us, however, wasn't the most pleasant person. We felt rushed with how he took our orders and felt like he wanted us to be out of there as quickly as possible. I got a burger with fries, which was okay. The cocktails were good, too. I don't think I'll visit again as I prefer a much quieter and relatively slow paced environment.

Service was top notch. Jalapeno Popper Burger  was a good unexpectedly sweet with a hint of spice. The Chicago Double Burger lived up to the hype. The Philly Cheese Steak had awesome flavor with tender beef, too small though. Tots were extra crispy, fries were well seasoned.

formatted_address: 29 E Ohio St, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: Pizzeria Uno

reviews.text:
Went here for dinner on a rainy Wednesday night. The place seemed reasonably full and we were told the wait to be seated would be 30-40 minutes. To get a place on the waiting list, however, they require you place a pizza order. So we did that and got on the waiting list. Within 30 seconds to a minute, we were called to be seated - that was the shortest 30-40 minutes ever!! Anyway, not complaining about being seared within 30 seconds of putting ourselves on a waiting list.

The restaurant felt very cozy but seemed to hold on to the old charm. The atmosphere was generally nice and welcoming. The staff were efficient and generally welcoming.

As a starter we ordered was the garlic bread. It came out quickly and was very cheesy. The taste of garlic, if there was any, was very mild. We all felt that the garlic bread would have benefited from more garlic and a lot less cheese. It felt very imbalanced.

For pizza, we made our own. The pizza took about 40 minutes. We ordered the large for our group of 4 and felt we could have done with smaller pizza. Apart from size, the pizza was generally ok. The crust, while good, wasn’t as good as the Lou Malnati’s crust. But the pizza wasn’t bad overall.

Overall, while the pizza wasn’t the best I’ve had, it wasn’t bad. I would certainly recommend this place.

I went to an Uno spot many years ago and remembering it being better. We had to order the pizza in order to get on the waiting list, which is a cool thing but it seemed to take a long time to get seated and get the food even though people before and after us didn’t seem to wait as long. When we got the pizza, it wasn’t exactly piping hot or anything. I would say the overall experience was okay, at best. I wouldn’t go back. I would recommend one of the other spots, like Pequods.

Definitely a lot of hype for pizza here we tried it out if I had to rate it between 10 being the best and being the worst, I give this a seven. Definitely worth trying out to check it off the bucket list but I would not give it a high-quality food rating. Yes it’s been around a long time, but the flavor is honestly kind of bland. The experience is awesome. The staff is amazing and the atmosphere is what’s to be expected when you’re eating an old-school Chicago pizza  It’s definitely a smaller restaurant with a bar inside. The seating is tight, but it’s definitely quaint and an experience. I definitely recommend trying this place out at least once to judge for yourself.

Stopped by Pizzeria Uno during my trip to Chicago and got to try their famous deep dish pizza! It does take about 30 minutes to bake, but trust me, it’s totally worth the wait. The crust was perfectly crispy, the cheese was melty and rich, and the sauce had such great flavor.

The restaurant has a warm, cozy vibe and the staff were super friendly and helpful, which made the experience even better. It really felt like a classic Chicago spot with a lot of history.

If you’re in town and curious about deep dish, this is a great place to start. Just come hungry and be ready to relax while it bakes, you won’t regret it!

The place of the original deep dish! We got a taste of the pizza during a bus tour, so we had to go back for seconds. We were told wait time would be about forty minutes, but fortunately they could take the pizza order ahead of time so we wouldn’t have to wait for the table and then another forty minutes for the pizza.

Once we sat down, we were very attended to. They brought the drinks quickly, refilling it before I needed to ask. Getting us new clean plates for the pizza after eating apps. The service was incredible, and the food just as good. We had some pasta along with pizza and it was worth the wait. I will definitely be coming back here!

formatted_address: 2121 N Clark St, Chicago, IL 60614, USA
name: Chicago Pizza and Oven Grinder Company

reviews.text: We visited Chicago from Saudi Arabia and one of my friends in US recommended this place for me. Amazing and unique pizza. Tasty and place is cozy. We had a service by Alvaro, he is an amazing guy very friendly, helpful and very professional. One of the best waiters I have ever met in my life. I wish him all the best. I wish we could come again to taste this delicious pizza and meet Alvaro, Thanks

This place went viral for a reason!

We went off tiktok recommendations and tried the Mediterranean bread and the 1lb pot pie (no mushrooms). The bread was a large, delicious portion sharable for 3-4 people. My daughter and I couldn’t stop eating on it while waiting for our pizza pot pie.

Then the magic happened when our wonderful server came out with it. The pot pie is such a good bite and the 1lber will feed two comfortably with the appetizer addition.

The service was excellent 👏 It’s a cozy little nook so servers walk by regularly checking on your experience. For being in Chicago i felt like the place was very affordable as well. Absolute must try!

Pizza pot pie?!?!?
I didn’t get it… then I did.  Don’t think of a  traditional “pot pie“.  It’s a delicious pile of pizza toppings and hearty pizza sauce on its own tarmac of crust. There’s not a doughy top; but do expect the best cheese on top as an umbrella of goodness.  Whatever you do, make sure you order the Mediterranean bread as an appetizer. You won’t be sorry. Not to mention, the salad was fresh and the perfect compliment to the pot pie.

Could not recommend this restaurant enough!

The atmosphere is incredible, super old school from the dark wooden booth to the jazz standards on the stereo. Our server was incredible, friendly, funny, and gave great recommendations!

The chef’s salad is just a vehicle for the Sour Cream and Garlic and Poppy Seed dressings — they are that good and even better when mixed together. The Mediterranean Bread was definitely my favorite item, smothered in garlic butter, their Italian seasoning blend is to die for and you will want to finish the whole thing, but then you won’t have room for the main attraction — the Pizza Pot Pie.

The red sauce is rich with spices from its 12 hour cook time, the Wisconsin Brick Cheese has all the qualities you’d want from a traditional mozzarella but with a thicker, cheesy flavor, and the crust is puff pastry adjacent and super doughy. A unique pizza experience in a city famous for its pizza.

We also got the Italian Combination and while it was good, I definitely could have done without it.

Chicago Pizza Oven is a hidden gem in the Windy City.

The menu is small, but they do it so well. The Mediterranean Bread is a must for an appetizer - big enough for at least four people. The Pizza Pot Pie is unique and delicious. Two people could get away with sharing a half pound, but it's so good that you might not want to share!

formatted_address: 2537 N Kedzie Blvd, Chicago, IL 60647, USA
name: Lula Cafe

reviews.text: One of the best breakfast burritos I’ve ever had. I like my breakfast burritos with a lot of egg and this was a good proportion. The pancakes were also great. Soft inside and crispy edges. Overall great dining will definitely be back!

Walked by this place a million times and finally ate there today. I’m vegan so usually just go to vegan restaurants but I tried their tofu vegetable scramble and it was ungodly delicious. Holy cow, could not believe how yummy it was. The atmosphere is so adorable, outdoor seating very nice, the staff was very nice, they give you a cute postcard with your bill, and I will definitely be back.

This place is wonderful. Good food, service and atmosphere.

Came here with a few co-workers and after work and really enjoyed our time here. Also appreciate they changed there happy hour to include tables (not just the bar).

The only thing I didn't like was that they added %20 automatically.

Cafe Robey never disappoints. The service is always exemplary. This staff is very attentive, yet not in your face about it. The energy is very relaxed. Seating is comfortable. And the food is absolutely delicious! They are absolutely wonderful about accommodating allergies. Every single time we have eaten here, we have had a wonderful experience. I can't say that about too many places.

When you're finished with your meal, go over by the front desk of the hotel, and hop in the elevator, and head on up to The Up Room on the roof for a wonderful cocktail! I promise you you will not regret that decision. It's the perfect way to wrap up an evening out! 10/10 we recommend Cafe Robey!

Lulas kitchen has slipped a bit. I remember loving the food. Now, I find it more bland, though not bad. I did enjoy the pancakes, but the burrito and briskets missed their mark. The rest of Lulas was great! All members of the staff were amazing. The place is comfortable and inviting. It's a great place to meet and bite. Great people watching. I'll be back again, but not soon.

formatted_address: 661 N La Salle Dr, Chicago, IL 60654, USA
name: Fogo de Chão Brazilian Steakhouse

reviews.text: Imagine traveling from another city to celebrate your birthday and choosing one of the restaurant that you thought would be great since you’ll see their ads everywhere and good review from other cities. No doubt we had one of the worst experience. The service was too slow and even if you turn your card green you have to ask your waiter two to three times if  there’s anyone who could serve you meat on your table. You have to wait for 20-30 minutes before you can have it. We also noticed that there’s one particular section where they will serve the meat and then will walk past our table. Our waiter (M) was nice and attentive and  will always ask whether we need anything. We also managed to talk to the manager (Will) and gave him an honest review. He was professional and polite and did a service recovery by giving us free desserts. I would say that the  $$$ that you’ll spent is not worth it, quality of the meat is  low and the service from the meat server is really bad, the only good thing that we had is their desserts. Definitely will be our first and last.

Great Service! This was my Mom's first time here.
Me and my brother surprised her with a Trip to Chicago.
(We live like 3hrs away) And a Mama's day surprise dinner.

And everyone was so great! She felt so special. We both really enjoyed it. And she's already asking when can we come back.

The food was great! Melt in your mouth, lamb chops, and the honey melted cheese soooo good!!
Thanks for giving my Mom a great first time experience! 💖💖

We had a wonderful experience eating at Fogo de Chão. During our dinner Carlos R. took care of us the entire evening and constantly checked in on us to ensure we were thoroughly satisfied with each and every aspect of our meal. He ensured preferred cuts of meat made it to our table again and again. Carlos made the difference in our night and I hope that he’s available every time we come back!! The salad bar was well stocked and we had our fill of unlimited sides and entrees. One of our best Rodizio Brazilian dinners.

Fogo de Chão offers an amazing experience, especially when it comes to their wide selection of condiments, salads, and appetizers before the main dishes—definitely a highlight. The variety of meats constantly brought to the table gives you that classic Brazilian steakhouse feel. We tried the “*Taste of Brazil*” for \$49, which felt like a good deal at first, but it quickly adds up—especially considering that premium cuts like ribeye, New York strip, and lamb chops aren't included.

Honestly, we mostly enjoyed the beef options, which were flavorful and cooked well. The pork selections were underwhelming—one cut was dry, and the pork belly was overly greasy and slimy. The bacon-wrapped chicken also didn’t impress. It was odd that the servers were passing us by with the meat skewers, and we had to specifically ask for more beef options to be brought over.

Overall, it’s a solid experience if you stick with the beef, and the ambiance is lively. Just keep in mind what’s included—and what’s not—before you commit to the deal.

I had such a great experience at Fogo de Chão — the food was absolutely delicious, and the entire team was incredibly attentive and friendly. I especially want to give a big shoutout to Oscar, the manager on duty, who went out of his way to make sure everything was perfect. He was welcoming, professional, and just genuinely kind — you can tell he truly cares about the guest experience. The whole night felt special thanks to him and the amazing staff. Can’t wait to come back!

formatted_address: 201 E Grand Ave, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: Volare Ristorante Italiano

reviews.text:
Didn't expect a bustling restaurant near my hotel would serve such wonderful dishes!

There is a whole system to this restaurant where everything has a high turnover rate and all the waiters and servers clean and serve very quickly. They are very attentive to each table so be sure to be firm when you're still working on a dish.

For 2 people, we ordered 1 pasta, 1 entree, and 1 appetizer. The best dish we had would be the seafood squid ink rose pasta. The seafood was generous, paired with some marvelous sauce, it was such a treat for both of us.

The appetizer was alright, and the veal had a great sauce too, though not a big fan of the texture. But the pasta overshadowed everything and that's all we could think about. We probably licked the plate clean because it was just so tasty. Highly recommend it!!

Note that even if you make a reservation at this restaurant, be sure to come by earlier because you'll end up having to wait anyway. We reserved for 7PM on a Tuesday and still had to wait for another 20 minutes before getting seated.

Come to feel right at home with family.  Exceptional food and service. Your welcoming bartender pours well balanced cocktails - I enjoyed a dirty martini with blue cheese olives (we are in Chicago, of course). Your waiter advises of the daily specials - some nice surprises. Your food arrives timely, hot and prepared to perfection. The Vitello alla Milanese and Gnocchi alla Vodka are fan favorites!!  The Ossobuco and Arancini on special reminded me of Milano. We paired with Rapini sautéed in garlic and olive oil. Large portions, fair prices and consistent, traditional flavors you remember from Nonna’s kitchen!  Enjoy,  Mangia! Note: we loved it so much we went back the next day to find the Burrata special pictured and the Linguini alla Vongole with Bottarga paired with a crisp glass of Vermentino. Brought me back to Sardegna. Just delicious!

I have carefully check the menus to find an Italian restaurant in this area that is the most reasonably priced with the worthy dishes to try. I came to conclude that Volare is the one and I decided to visit. Well, I am already satisfied with a warm bread, decent olive oil, and imported thick balsamic vinegar. You can see the quality of this place from simply these starters. We then got grilled seafood. Fresh and generous. The highlight though is the lobster spaghetti in the shrimp sauce. Well, the price tag for the dish is already well matched for lobster. So it feels like the shrimp spaghetti is just for free. Well, what amazed me is not just how meaty and sweet the lobster is, but also how well spiced and seasoned the pasta is. It is so enjoyable! Last but not least, we got the tiramisu that our server kindly recommended. It is so awesome that we can devour the whole thing without any struggle even after all savory dishes. I am definitely willing to come back and enjoy everything from beginning to end over again!

Beautiful resturante with exceptional service and pasta to die for. We didnt make a reservation, but were sat immediatley and quickly a server approached. We had the Linguine and Garganelli dishes, each superb flavors leaving us wanting more.
We also experiences their tiramisu and cappucinnos, light and the perfect way to end our dining experience here.

We had a wonderful dinner yesterday! The food was excellent, and the service was exceptional. Despite the crowded restaurant , they managed to find us a seat. We ordered the Insalata Volare salad, Nodino di Vitello Milanese, Primi Garaanelli al Ragu di Manzo, and Primi Ravioli di Ricotta. Everything was delicious!

formatted_address: 1927 W North Ave, Chicago, IL 60622, USA
name: Piece Pizzeria and Brewery

reviews.text:
Decent pizza, could be more New Haven like. Some slices were really thin and had a great crust and bite.

Others were more doughy and NYC like.

Very good pizza, I just expected it to be a little more thin

Ordered a 1/2 1/2 Hot Doug’s and Veggie Pizza (to be healthy of course). While it was just the two of us we got a large because it was just a few more bucks. Turns out the sizes match because there was enough pizza leftover for another person or two; would recommend if you want leftovers like us.

The pizza itself was awesome, flavorful and delicious, always get Hot Doug’s!Paired with their brews and it brought the meal together! The wait staff were busy working but were always attentive and really made our night. The place is loud (especially if you sat next to kids/babes) but it makes sense because the pizza is great for families, couples, and everyone in-between.

Would come again and be completely stuffed with good pizza!

If you’re on the hunt for outstanding pizza in a lively atmosphere, Piece Brewery is a must! Visited on a Friday night, and let me tell you, this place was packed—a clear sign that something special was happening here. We ordered the Hot Doug’s Atomic Sausage Pizza, and from the first bite, we knew we’d hit the jackpot. But we didn’t see what a night and experience was going to be with the food!

This red pizza features a thin, crispy crust that’s both light and perfectly sturdy, giving each slice an incredible base for flavor. The pepper jack cheese melted smoothly over the crust, bringing a subtle spicy creaminess that paired beautifully with the toppings. The caramelized onions added a sweet depth that balanced out the heat, while Hot Doug’s famous Atomic Sausage was simply next-level. Juicy and bursting with spices, this sausage was the real star—it packed a punch of bold, unique flavors that I haven’t tasted anywhere else. Every ingredient was placed with precision, creating a beautifully layered experience in every bite.

Piece Brewery nails the thin crust game and takes pizza to new heights with unique, crave-worthy flavors. Even with the crowd, the service was on point and efficient. This place is an absolute gem, and I can’t wait to return!

Nice atmosphere to watch sports. Could definitely see this place being packed with nicer weather outside.

Ordered the hot Doug’s atomic pizza. I was intrigued with this as I’ve never had pepper jack cheese on my pizza but was quickly disappointed as I couldn’t really taste it. The sausage and onions were alright. Crust was very floppy and the entire pie was drenched in grease. Also, I chuckled a little with how uneven these slices were.

While the pizza wasn’t the best, the carrot cake was excellent. The cake was so moist and light. Also, the nuts and raisins were sparse which I prefer in my carrot cake. Finally, the cream cheese frosting was good but there wasn’t enough.

Good atmosphere and dessert, not so good pizza.

As a native Chicagoan (lived there 50 years before moving on), I have strong opinions about pizza.  I'm old enough to remember old fashioned 1970s deep dish pizza, and the 1990s emergence of the now more popular tavern style pizza.   And I like them all.

But my favorite Chicago pizza is not really Chicago pizza at all.   It's the New Haven style pizza served at Piece Brewery.   Whenever I'm in Chicago, this is always one of my first stops.   It is one of those places that's just perfect, and I hope it never changes.

I always get a red pizza, with added clams and garlic.   Yes, I said clams.   Don't knock it until you try it.

Piece is also noteworthy for being one of Chicago's very first brewpubs, going way back to the beginning of the modern craft beer movement.  Their beer brewed in house is still pretty good, and goes great with the pizza.

formatted_address: corner of Grand & McClurg, 355 E Ohio St, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: Yolk - Streeterville

reviews.text:
Had a great breakfast this morning at Yolk in downtown Chicago. I came with my wife, and we both left impressed. I ordered the corned beef hash, and they had the steak and eggs—both dishes came with pancakes, which were light, fluffy, and a nice bonus. Everything was cooked well and full of flavor. Our server, James, was friendly, attentive, and kept the coffee topped off without even having to ask.

Only small critique was that the hash browns were a bit on the dry side, but it didn’t take away from the overall experience. The atmosphere was bright and welcoming, and the service made the meal even better. Definitely a solid spot for breakfast in the city.

The waitress was great.  The atmosphere..not so much.  The tables are too close together and there is little room to sit and maneuver.  It feels like people are sitting with you at your table or you are at theirs.  Way too close.

I had the Works Omelette, but everything was scrambled together and shaped into a loaf.  I call these Lazy Omelettes.  It was good but not what I ordered.  Just because you call it an omelet, it does not make it an omelet if it is scrambled together. Just call it what it is" The Works Scramble".

Monica had scrambled eggs with cheese. If they had shaped it into a loaf it would have been a cheese omelette.

The Banana Nut French Toast was awesome though!

The food is good, but 66$ to not get the omelet you expect is disappointing.

The female bathroom was pretty nasty also.

Thanks for the reply.  It sounds like a lazy omelet and a rolled omelet are the same things.  I have been calling scrambled eggs shaped like a loaf a lazy omelet for about 10 years.  It is still a type of omelet, but not an omelet, hence the name....lazy/rolled omelet.

The staff was welcoming as soon as we entered. We started with their amazing strawberry lemonade and an iced latte. I had Eggs Benedict & my son had his favorite scrambled eggs with bacon. It was also served with cheesy grits. They have so many other delicious options but we were too full to try anything else but that just means we need to come back!

Definitely a beehive of staffing actively on a busy Memorial Day weekend.  Food was just ok, not much taste.  Staff were friendly and efficient.  Immediate bar seating was graciously accepted and appreciated to avoid another breakfast restaurant wait.

We went there because it’s a famous breakfast chain in Chicago. We had the Breakfast of the Day. One serving was enough for two people. The food was a typical American breakfast, but with smoked salmon, which made it different. It wasn’t amazing, but it was unique. Keep it in mind if you decide to go.

formatted_address: 1015 N Rush St, Chicago, IL 60611, USA
name: Tavern On Rush

reviews.text:
Absolutely fantastic experience at Tavern on Rush!

The hospitality was outstanding — Benny & Juan made us feel so welcome and went above and beyond to ensure we had a great time.

The atmosphere is lively yet classy, perfect for both lunch and an evening treat. We had the tuna tartare and burger for lunch, both incredibly fresh and delicious.

We loved it so much we came back later for dessert! Highly recommend for anyone looking for top-notch service, amazing food, and a great vibe.

Sure! Here's a polished review that includes the beautiful bar and great people-watching location:

---

This spot absolutely delivers! The atmosphere is vibrant without trying too hard — you walk in and immediately feel like you made the right choice. The bar is stunning, beautifully designed with just the right balance of style and warmth. It’s the kind of place you want to linger, whether you're sipping something classic or trying one of their creative cocktails.

What really sets this place apart is the location. It’s prime for people-watching — grab a seat near the window or outside and you’ve got a front-row view of the city’s characters and charm passing by. Perfect for a casual night out or impressing out-of-town guests. Great drinks, beautiful space, and unbeatable vibes.

Highly recommend.

We went for dessert! The chocolate cake is big enough for 4 people!! So moist and just the right amount of sweetness! Vanilla ice cream is a must to eat with the decadent cake! The apple pie was also phenomenal! The sweet apples were tasty and the crust was so flaky.

Stayed in the hotel here so only had the breakfast provided as a Hyatt globalist. Was here for four days so ate daily and the service staff was great. Not crowded at breakfast from Monday to Thursday so you have the staff to your self. I heard this place gets a bit rowdy in the evening but there is an upstairs bar you enter in the hotel lobby that has about 6 seats so if you want something a bit more low key, then go upstairs to the smaller bar. See pics for all the breakfast we ate for freezy and we did order some pasta at the upstairs bar.  Again our breakfast was free some prices below do not reflect actual breakfast cost but most dishes were about $16 bucks average.

We stayed at the Thompson Hotel, which is conveniently connected to Tavern On Rush, and found ourselves popping in and out throughout our trip. It’s consistently busy—a clear sign that people love it—and the vibrant atmosphere definitely lived up to the hype. The location in the heart of the Gold Coast is unbeatable. We enjoyed several rounds of drinks at the bar and grabbed quick bites like the fried rice and potstickers—both were fantastic. We thoroughly enjoyed our experience and can’t wait to come back!

formatted_address: 2207 N Clybourn Ave, Chicago, IL 60614, USA
name: Pequod's Pizza

reviews.text: Busy night, but we snatched a couple of seats at the bar.  For someone who doesn't get deep dish in my area, it was a welcome change to my normal pizza experience. We opted for a spinach, basil, onion pizza. It was delicious. If you haven't tried deep dish before, give it a shot.  Is it cooked in a cast iron pan and has a thick bread crust that goes all the way up the sides, and the rim is crusted with burnt cheese. The sauce is heavy on the marinara with ample toppings throughout. We also had a tavern style, thin crust pizza with Italian beef and jalapeños, Just as delicious. Service was good. Wait time was about the expected 40 minutes. Parking was a bit of a challenge because there were a lot of people in the area for a Cubs game.

I have been wanting to try Pequod’s pizza for a few years and simply never had the chance. On a recent trip to the Chicago area I finally made the trip. Honestly, this has to be hands down the best Chicago style pizza I have ever had. The sauce was beautifully seasoned, has a sweet taste to it. The cheese was nice, not too heavy and had a great taste. The toppings were fresh, and excellent quality. Definitely the sausage is house made and was delicious. The crust was the star of the show, not too dense, nice and buttery flavour, and the crispy cheese edge was the icing on the cake. The service was good, ordered over the phone and the pizza was ready right on time. I would definitely recommend you try out Pequod’s Pizza if you are in the area or even outside the area.

Pequod's Pizza in Chicago is an absolute gem of a pizza place. The pan and thin crust pizzas are out of this world delicious. The crust is perfectly crispy on the outside and soft on the inside, and the toppings are always fresh and flavorful.

But what really sets Pequod's apart is their amazing service. The staff is always friendly and attentive, making sure that every customer has a great experience. They go above and beyond to ensure that your dining experience is top-notch, from recommending the perfect pizza to making sure your drinks are always topped off.

The cozy and inviting atmosphere of the restaurant only adds to the overall experience. Whether you're dining in or taking your pizza to go, Pequod's will always leave you satisfied and craving more. I highly recommend this place to anyone looking for a delicious pizza and exceptional service in Chicago.

Pequod’s Pizza
⭐️ 5/5
📍 2207 N Clybourn Ave, Chicago, IL

This spot came highly recommended by Chicago locals as the place for deep dish. After trying it, I totally get the hype. Pequod’s delivers big flavor, premium toppings, and that unforgettable caramelized crust that sets it apart.

What I Ordered:

Deep Dish with Pepperoni, Mushrooms, Onions, Spinach and Sausage

Side of ranch (a must with the crust)

What I Loved:
The caramelized crust is a game changer. It’s crispy, slightly smoky, and adds so much flavor to every bite. It holds up perfectly under the cheese and toppings without getting soggy.

The toppings are generous and clearly high quality. The sausage was well seasoned, the pepperoni had just the right crisp, and the veggies were fresh and still had texture. Every slice felt thoughtful and hearty.

The sauce is rich and savory with just enough tang. It works with the crust instead of overpowering the whole pie like some deep dish can.

Heads Up:
The wait is real. Even with a reservation, the pizza takes around 45 minutes to bake. The space gets crowded and loud during peak hours, so plan ahead and don’t come starving.

Pro Tips:

Locals swear by it, and now I do too

Make a reservation online to save time

A medium pizza goes a long way

Get the ranch, it’s worth it

Reheat leftovers in a pan for that crispy edge

Final Take:
If you’re visiting Chicago or just looking for a standout deep dish spot, Pequod’s should be on your list. Locals know best, and they were right about this one. I’d come back without hesitation.

Fun little hole in the wall pizza joint. Great atmosphere .. filled with good energy. The place was still popping at 1 AM on a weekday !!
We were seated immediately and our server wasn’t far behind. Very present and attentive .. friendly and kind.
Good was some of the best I’ve eaten in a long time.  Cheesy garlic bread was crispy and soft at the same time. Full of cheesy, garlicky, buttery goodness .. and the dipping sauce was just the right touch.

Pizza was a tad overcooked .. however that is how I like it. Fresh toppings. Full flavored sauce.

Meatball sub was one of the best sandwiches we have eaten. Ever.

Highly recommend this local favorite spot. Great food. Excellent service. Fun vibe.

formatted_address: 1401 S Michigan Ave, Chicago, IL 60605, USA
name: The Chicago Firehouse Restaurant

reviews.text: What an icon and the best service in town! Hidden patio in the back too! So historical. Their new spring menu is amazing with fried morels and soft shell crab panazella! Get their lobster and coconut cream pie. The spring margarita was terrific too.

We booked a private room here for our wedding "reception". The food is tasty; all of our guests were really pleased.
